Lime and the adult dataset¶

This tutorial goes through the library called Lime which is a explainable AI model. It highlights different features that have the biggest impact on the classification.

For this tutorial we also use the adult dataset which is availble from> https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/adult It contains data gathered from an American Census database and you can read more about it from the description availble.

# First we have a list of the features in the dataset which we can use if we
# want to make our dataset more understandable. 
# Secondly we call sklearn's labelEncoder as Lime only can use numerical data, Therefor
#we use SKlearns LabelEncoder to transform the categorical features to numerical ones
#Another is that it need to have 
feature_names = ["Age", "Workclass", "fnlwgt", "Education", "Education-Num", "Marital Status","Occupation",
                 "Relationship", "Race", "Sex", "Capital Gain", "Capital Loss","Hours per week", "Country"]

#Here you need to add the address to where you stored the adult dataset:
data = np.genfromtxt('adult.data', delimiter=', ', dtype=str)



labels = data[:,14]
le= sklearn.preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
le.fit(labels)
labels = le.transform(labels)
class_names = le.classes_
data = data[:,:-1]
In [4]:
# Lime has a set of preconditions and one of them is that the data needs to 
# We need to specify which features are categorical and then apply the label encoder 
#so that it is aware which features when everything is numerical is a categorical
categorical_features = [1,3,5, 6,7,8,9,13]
categorical_names = {}
for feature in categorical_features:
    le = sklearn.preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
    le.fit(data[:, feature])
    data[:, feature] = le.transform(data[:, feature])
    categorical_names[feature] = le.classes_
In [5]:
#Making the data as float type now for a encoder which is used on
#the categorical features to one hot encode them. This meaning each used category is 
#turned into its own feature. But Sckit learn have a model called ColumnTransformer
#Which will go through all the columns we specify and applying the function you want 
#to that column. Here we intiate it
data = data.astype(float)


from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer 
encoder = ColumnTransformer([("enc", sklearn.preprocessing.OneHotEncoder(), categorical_features)], remainder = 'passthrough')

predict_fn = lambda x: rf.predict_proba(encoder.transform(x)).astype(float)

Applying Lime to our dataset. We give it the training data along with the name of the features we use, and the string representation of the categorical values in the data. If you are more intrested in how it works the docs is linked here: https://lime-ml.readthedocs.io/en/latest/lime.html

In [11]:
explainer = lime.lime_tabular.LimeTabularExplainer(train ,feature_names = feature_names,class_names=class_names,
                                                   categorical_features=categorical_features, 
                                                   categorical_names=categorical_names, kernel_width=3)

Limes explanations or showcase of the different weights of the features for a entry and in what they contribute. In this example it is a huge weight on Capital Gain as for this dataset, if we do not clean or controll this feature it will have a huge impact. Because there is not that many entries with capital Gain but of those few that have they are actually more likely to make over 50K even if their capital gain is miniscule.
